  "prompt": "What is the difference between adding and committing in Git?",
  "response": "Here's a clear explanation of the difference between adding and committing in Git:\n\nAdding (git add):\n- Stages specific changes in your working directory\n- Prepares files to be included in the next commit\n- Moves changes from the working directory to the staging area\n- Does not permanently save changes\n- Example:\n```bash\ngit add filename.txt     # Stage a specific file\ngit add .                # Stage all changes\n```\n\nCommitting (git commit):\n- Creates a permanent snapshot of staged changes\n- Saves changes to the local Git repository\n- Adds a commit message describing the changes\n- Marks a specific point in the project's history\n- Example:\n```bash\ngit commit -m \"Add new feature\"      # Commit staged changes\ngit commit -am \"Update description\"  # Stage and commit in one step\n```\n\nWorkflow visualization:\n1. Working Directory \u2192 Staging Area (git add)\n2. Staging Area \u2192 Repository (git commit)\n\nAnalogy:\n- Adding = Preparing items to pack in a box\n- Committing = Sealing and labeling the box for storage\n\nBest practices:\n- Make small, focused commits\n- Write clear, descriptive commit messages\n- Commit frequently to track progress",
